              <otmi:snippet>A deep subsurface biosphere exists today, and by some estimates it is as massive as the one on the Earth&apos;s surface</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>A few of the pieces connect, but many of them don&apos;t, and most are missing</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>All in all, I take the data at face value, and accept that the authors have probably uncovered the oldest-known samples of biologically produced gas</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Another intriguing aspect to Ueno and colleagues&apos; research is its geological setting</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Between 3.5 billion and 3.45 billion years ago, a series of lavas known as pillow basalts, and sedimentary rocks, were deposited in what is now the Dresser Formation</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But the presence of life within Earth&apos;s crust, combined with good evidence for life in surface environments, suggest that by 3.5 billion years ago the Earth was teeming with microorganisms.</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But we can be certain that an active biosphere was in place</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>By contrast, the methane from the primary inclusions was much more strongly depleted in 13 C, and is consistent with a microbial origin</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Carbon isotopes of this type, however, cannot tell us which organisms were present</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Evidence for the activities of sulphate-reducing bacteria, which use sulphate rather than oxygen in energy production, has been reported from the Dresser Formation </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>For further insights into early Earth ecosystems, we zoom forward around 300 million years to the Dresser Formation in Western Australia</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Fossil structures known as stromatolites, which are probably of biological origin, have been found in slightly younger rocks from the same stratigraphic sequence </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Here, a series of organic remains has been interpreted as possibly being those of cyanobacteria </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>However, microbial mats have been identified in 3.42-billion-year-old rocks from South Africa , and the chemistry of the rocks indicates that anoxygenic phototrophs (photosynthetic organisms that do not produce oxygen) were probably the dominant mat-forming organisms</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In their investigations, Ueno et al . crushed samples of quartz ( Fig. 1 ) and measured the concentrations of the extracted gases and the isotopic composition of the methane carbon</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>It is from here that Ueno et al . ( page 516 of this issue) report evidence for the existence of an ancient population of methane- producing microbes, commonly known as methanogens</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>It was probably quite complex, including many of the components of modern anaerobic ecosystems</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Many of the bubbles align along the growth margins of the quartz, and so are believed to have formed as the quartz was precipitated: they are viewed as primary inclusions</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Might all of the methane have a non-biological source? The authors anticipate this argument and note that their primary fluid inclusions lack the higher (C 2+ ) hydrocarbons that are normally associated with the most strongly 13 C-depleted thermogenic methane</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Of these, we can identify anoxygenic phototrophs, sulphate reducers and methanogens</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Other bubbles are scattered randomly within the quartz (and are probably primary), while still others are concentrated where the quartz was fractured and resealed</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Piecing together the early history of life from the geological record is like putting together an incomplete jigsaw puzzle</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Small bubbles (fluid inclusions) are found within quartz minerals in the dykes, and these bubbles contain mainly carbon dioxide and water, but also some methane (CH 4 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>So whether or not cyanobacteria were present is crucial to our understanding of the nature of the biosphere 3.5 billion years ago</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Still, the isotopic composition of the methane from the primary inclusions is not very different from that of the most 13 C-depleted, thermally formed methane</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The basalts were intruded by numerous silica dykes, some of which terminate in the sedimentary layers (see Fig. 1 of the paper on page 517)</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The evidence, found in the isotopic composition of organic carbon , is rather scarce, but it is compelling</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The organisms involved in stromatolite growth are unknown</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The primary and secondary inclusions contained methane with distinct isotopic compositions</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The results of Ueno et al . do not tell us anything about the magnitude of the ancient subsurface biosphere</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The secondary inclusions had a composition consistent with (but not proof of) a non-biological, thermal source of methane that was probably introduced some time after the silica dykes were first in place</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The silica dykes housing the methane originated from deep in Earth&apos;s crust — maybe as much as 1 kilometre below the surface </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The story is this</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>These are viewed as secondary inclusions</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>These results, therefore, point to an active subsurface biosphere</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This is not the normal bubbly lake or coastal marine sediment usually associated with methanogenesis</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This means that the dykes are ancient and were formed during the deposition of the sediments</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This represents one of the earliest specific microbial processes to have been identified in the geological record: it adds an extra piece to the emerging picture of the structure and complexity of ancient microbial ecosystems</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>To explore this issue, we return to Western Australia and to the Apex Chert, which is slightly younger than the Dresser Formation</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Unfortunately, a cyanobacterial affiliation cannot be decided by morphology alone, and the interpretation of these remains as biogenic is controversial </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>We cannot, therefore, be confident that oxygen-producing organisms existed 3.5 billion years ago</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>We know — or at least we think we know — that life evolved by 3.8 billion years ago</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>What about oxygen? An aerobic biosphere was not possible before the evolution of oxygen-producing cyanobacteria, and oxygen-producing photosynthesis accomplishes the vast majority of the primary production today</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>With this backdrop, let us enquire more broadly into the nature of life 3.5 billion years ago</otmi:snippet>
            </otmi:snippets>
